Our best-sounding Echo speaker yet

You've never heard an Echo like this before. Echo Studio is the only Echo speaker that creates an immersive, 3-dimensional soundscape, wrapping you in studio-quality audio from every direction. You can also ask Alexa to set alarms, control compatible smart home devices, check the weather, play a song and more. Learn more about Alexa features.

Make your music sound incredible

Human ears care where sound is coming from. Echo Studio turns that evolutionary truth into a revolutionary advantage. Five strategically positioned speakers generate room-filling sound, sending different parts of the song to your ears from different directions. This means you can hear studio-quality music as the artist intended.

“Alexa, play the Best of Spatial Audio playlist.”

Experience room-filling sound

Spatial audio processing technology is customised to fit the acoustic design of Echo Studio, featuring stereo up-mixing and spatial virtualisation to provide immersive studio-quality sound for your stereo audio and home cinema system.

With room-adaption technology, Echo Studio automatically analyses the acoustics of your space, fine-tuning playback for optimal sound, no matter where it’s placed.

Enjoy your favourite audio content

Stream all of your favourite music, podcasts and audiobooks with Amazon Music, Apple Music, Spotify, Deezer and more. An Amazon Music Unlimited subscription gives you access to millions of songs in Ultra HD and a fast-growing collection of spatial audio.

Help keep your smart home connected

Built-in smart home hub

Connect to and manage your smart home with the built-in hub. Just switch on compatible products and say, “Alexa, discover my devices”. Alexa will automatically detect and set them up so you can control lights, plugs and more with your voice. This simple setup process works with dozens of compatible devices that use Zigbee. Echo Studio also supports every Works with Alexa device. Learn more about Alexa Smart Home.

“Alexa, discover my devices.”

Alexa is happy to help

Make your life easier at home. Use your voice to set timers, add items to lists, and create calendar events and reminders. You can also check the news, weather or traffic. Ask for sports scores, film times, restaurant hours or information. Learn more about Alexa Productivity.

“Alexa, what's on my calendar?”

Do more with device pairing

Echo Studio + another Echo
Fill your home with music using compatible Echo devices in different rooms. Learn more about Multi-Room Audio.

Echo Studio + Fire TV
Watch TV with immersive sound when you set up Alexa Home Cinema with compatible devices. Learn more about Alexa Home Cinema.

Designed to protect your privacy

Alexa and Echo devices are built with multiple layers of privacy protection. For example, Echo Studio has a Microphone Off button that electronically disconnects the microphones. You also have control over your voice recordings. Learn more about how you can view, hear or delete them at any time.

Simple to set up and use

Step 1

Place at least 15 cm from wall with clearance above and on all sides.

Step 2

Download the latest version of the Amazon Alexa app.

Step 3

Plug in your Echo Studio and wait for Alexa to greet you.

Step 4

Set up your device in the Alexa app.

Technical details

Echo Studio

Size

206 x 175 mm (height x diameter)

Weight

3.5 kg
Actual size and weight may vary by manufacturing process.

Audio

Three 51 mm midrange speakers, a 25 mm tweeter, a 133 mm woofer with bass aperture to maximise bass output.

Amplifier

Peak output 330 W; 24-bit DAC; 100 kHz bandwidth

Supported audio formats

FLAC, MP3, AAC, Opus, Vorbis, Dolby Digital, Dolby Digital Plus, Dolby Atmos and Sony 360 Reality Audio/MPEG-H; includes support for CD Quality (16-bit) and Hi-Res (up to 24-bit).

Supported music-streaming services

Amazon Music, Apple Music, Spotify, Deezer, TuneIn and more.

Automatic room adaptation

Analyses the acoustics of the room and continuously adjusts audio filters during music playback to optimise sound output regardless of placement (device must not be muted).

Spatial audio processing technology

Spatial audio processing technology is a digital audio processing technology that produces a more forward sound with greater width, clarity and presence that envelops the listener.

Audio input

Combination 3.5 mm mini-optical TOSLINK.

Fire TV compatibility

Connects wirelessly as the audio output for Fire TV - Learn more about compatibility Set up audio system using the Alexa app.

Wi-Fi connectivity

Dual-band Wi-Fi supports 802.11 a/b/g/n/ac (2.4 and 5 GHz) networks. Does not support connecting to ad-hoc (or peer-to-peer) Wi-Fi networks.

Zigbee connectivity

Built-in Zigbee smart home hub supports Zigbee light bulbs, locks, sensors, plugs and in-wall switches. See all Zigbee compatible devices.

Bluetooth connectivity

Advanced Audio Distribution Profile (A2DP) support for audio streaming from your mobile device to Echo or from Echo to your Bluetooth speaker. Audio/Video Remote Control Profile (AVRCP) to control connected mobile devices with voice. Hands-free voice control is not supported for Mac OS X devices. Bluetooth speakers requiring PIN codes are not supported.

Setup technology

Amazon Wi-Fi simple setup enables customers to connect smart devices to their Wi-Fi network in a few easy steps. Wi-Fi simple setup is another way Alexa is always getting smarter. Learn more about setup technology.

Warranty and service

Amazon Echo Studio is sold with a limited warranty of one year provided by the manufacturer. If you are a consumer, the limited warranty is in addition to your consumer rights, and does not jeopardise these rights in any way. This means you may still have additional rights at law even after the limited warranty has expired (click here for further information on your consumer rights). Use of Amazon Echo Studio is subject to the terms found here.

Accessibility features

The Alexa app and Alexa-enabled products include several features for customers with accessibility needs related to vision, hearing, mobility and speech. Learn more about Alexa accessibility.

Included in the box

Echo Studio, power cable and Quick Start Guide.

Privacy features

Wake word technology, streaming indicators, Microphone Off button, the ability to view and delete your voice recordings and more. Visit the Alexa Privacy Hub to explore how Alexa and Echo devices are designed to protect your privacy.

Language

Alexa speaks English, German, French, Italian and Spanish.

Software security updates

This device receives guaranteed software security updates until at least four years after the device is last available for purchase as a new unit on our websites. Learn more about these software security updates. If you already own an Amazon Echo, visit Manage Your Content and Devices for information specific to your device.

Alexa app

The Amazon Alexa app is compatible with Fire OS, Android and iOS devices. See a list of supported operating systems.

How customer reviews and ratings work

Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings, help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we don’t use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyses reviews to verify trustworthiness.

5.0 out of 5 stars Great sound, much better than previous models.
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 11 November 2019
As soon as it was up and running it was clear the sound was much better than my previous model. This was a first generation so the improvement was very noticeable. This performs much closer to something like a Bose speaker of the same size but at half the price. Listening to radio stations is now a real pleasure and at the moment you can access a 3D playlist as part of the standard Amazon Prime music service. It’s very impressive, in particular The Beatles ‘Come Together’ 3D mix sounds amazing, especially from such a relatively small box!Having Zigbee built in is very useful too. There are lots of Zigbee products out there now and notably Philips Hue bulbs can work directly with the speaker without an additional hub.As usual the integration with other Amazon family products works well. Using a voice command I can view my Blink cameras through the TV using and Amazon Fire stick. Everything is intuitive and easy to set up.It looks like the launch has been a huge success as there is currently a wait for new stock. In my view it’s worth holding out for this Echo model, it ticks all the boxes and provides great sound from a relatively small footprint. I love it!

2.0 out of 5 stars Multiple problems. 4K Max Firestick to Echo Studio loses connection every day.
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 30 June 2022
Colour Name: CharcoalStyle Name: Device onlyVerified Purchase
I was excited to get this speaker, as it meant I could play Atmos via the 4K Max Firestick to the Echo Studio. Except it doesn't work correctly, and there are multiple threads across the net complaining about it. It will work for a while, but as soon as you switch the TV off, it loses the connection. There is now no sound coming from the Echo Studio, the Studio is silent, and the ONLY way to get the sound back again is to reboot the Firestick every damn time. I have spoken to Amazon about this several times and it still hasn't been fixed.

OTHER ISSUES

When the TV is off songs fail to play. The Echo Studio is connected to the Firestick, via the Amazon Alexa phone app (the home theatre option), and yes, the songs fail to play. Usually playlists work but individual songs often don't. Alexa will start playing the song and then the song will go silent, the sound will return part way through the song or on to the next song - if it's a playlist. If you switch the TV on, the amazon music app will come on the TV and then the songs will play.

1 This is wasting electricity, having to have the TV on all the time, when playing the Echo Studio.
2 It is risking burn in due to the static logos on the amazon music app.

The songs should play with the TV off, but they do not unless you unplug the firestick from your TV, which will end up breaking the connection eventually.

LOOPING. I have had Alexa playing the same song over and over again, until I tell it to stop. When you ask Alexa to stop repeat she says, I cannot stop looping in the amazon music prime account, whatever that means? This issue thankfully seemed to fix itself.

ERROR MESSAGE. Alexa says - I'm having trouble playing music from your library - during playing a song, which is playing! Sigh. She said this while playing every song for a while.

BASICALLY - if you just wanna play Amazon music on the Studio, it will likely work, in regular, HD, UHD or 3D. I'm not sure I can honestly tell the difference between the different formats. I suppose the HD / UHD sound slightly better but it's not a night and day difference from regular Alexa, why? Likely because the Studio is a decent speaker anyway, and likely because HD, UHD and 3D is overrated. Perhaps the human ear has trouble hearing anything after HD.

Yes, when it works it's very good! The Atmos sound is superb from this one speaker and it is very loud, and clear, with convincing effects, from up, down, left and right, BUT it doesn't work correctly with the home theatre setup - as discussed above. Therefore at present, it isn't fit for purpose...

When connected with the Firestick (via the Amazon Alexa phone app), it constantly cuts out on songs and goes silent, when the TV is off. When movie / TV show sound is playing from the Firestick to the Studio, the sound cuts out every day, and it needs rebooting, every day. It is infuriating tech.

TIP. Make sure you have the 4K Max Firestick in the arc / earc connection on your TV to get Atmos. Amazon advised me to use an aux cable to connect the Firestick to the Studio directly, but you won't get Atmos that way, as you need an arc / earc connection. When it works, the sound will also play from an Apple TV box / the TV apps, through the Firestick to the Studio. But that's when it works.

Amazon need to fix the above issues with a firmware update, if they can, otherwise I will have to remove the home theatre connection. I will only be able to use it as an Alexa speaker - on its own, and the 4K Firestick will then be useless to me. Money down the drain.

EDIT. I'm still having problems with this. The latest issue is: Alexa is cutting the end of songs off before going onto the next one in a playlist. It has also started looping the same song again. This was without it being connected to the firestick, using the Studio on its own. I'm not sure if mine is faulty, if it's the internet - I have 100 meg, or what? Sigh. We never had this trouble with vinyl / CD's.

EDIT. I returned it. It's not worth the hassle. I bought an Echo 4 and it seems to be working correctly so far. To be honest, I can't tell the difference in sound quality. Echo 4 is MP3 / HD max only and the Studio is HD / UHD / 3D, but they almost - practically sound the same. The Studio is probably slightly better due to it being a better speaker, but in blind tests people couldn't tell the difference between HD and UHD. It's not like 4K HDR where there is a big difference in picture quality! HD is CD quality and most people can't hear better than that. MP3 is obviously inferior, on paper, but even when I had the Studio in one room and a regular Echo in the other, I'm not sure there was a real, noticeable difference. Unless you're listening to them side by side, it is difficult to remember what the HD sounded like, and the MP3 still sounds great. I don't feel like I'm missing anything with having the Echo 4. The Studio for HD / UHD costs an extra £5 a month. 3D sounded different, I wouldn't say it was necessarily better or even needed. Besides there isn't much 3D content at the moment.

As for the Atmos, well it just doesn't work. The Studio loses connection with the Firestick every day. I am now using an optical lead from the TV with a 3.5 jack on the other end, plugged into the Echo 4. It's not Atmos, no, but it should improve the sound for games / concerts / movies - somewhat. If not I might buy a soundbar, keep in mind this is for a bedroom and not a living room.

Until Amazon fix the Echo Studio and make sure it can't / doesn't lose connection with the 4K Firestick every day, it isn't fit for purpose. Especially with all the other problems mentioned above.

Very, very good sound, particularly from such a compact device - being honest, I cannot really tell it apart from the system it replaced - an older high-end hi-fi separates system. Plenty of volume available in most normal sized rooms - works perfectly OK in ours, a large walk-through lounge/ dining room. Plenty of bass too, which was a big surprise - I'd mentally ticked off treating myself for Christmas with the Bass booster unit, available, but doubt I would bother now. Its been tried in several locations, including on the floor in the corner of the room, stood on furniture unit, and also on a large, solid bookshelf - location makes no discernable difference to volume, bass, or quality, as the on-board electronics are adaptive and very clever (and due to get a free online software upgrade, too!) Set-up was simple enough if you just follow the instructions. So...... I grew up with loads of rock music from some of the classics - Deep Purple, Hendrix, Led Zeppelin etc, all of which really need to have a bit of volume to enjoy - so I bought a second Studio, intending to link it with the first - hammers out volume and bass (together with Dolby Atmos) when they are located in the same room, but plays equally well if they are placed in different rooms, even one upstairs and the other downstairs. Very happy to recommend these units, and will likely buy at least a couple more Alexa-based devices from the range, with screens, for my lads, to allow them to watch video, as audio streams.
